{"title":"ForceSight: Text-Guided Mobile Manipulation with Visual-Force Goals","domain":"ROBOTICS","seeds":[{"problem":"Language-guided mobile manipulation in novel environments requires predicting not only where to act but also how much force to apply; most prior goal predictors focus on kinematics alone, leading to failures in contact-rich tasks.","method":"ForceSight is a text-conditioned RGBD vision transformer that predicts visual-force goals (kinematic + force) from a single eye-in-hand RGBD image and a natural-language prompt. It extends a ViT-L pre-trained on ImageNet-21k with an RGBD patch embedding (early fusion for depth) and injects a frozen T5 text embedding via cross-attention at every transformer block. The network outputs a 224×224 affordance map and a depth map to recover a 3D gripper target in the camera frame (argmax over affordance; masked L1 depth), and MLP heads predict yaw, gripper width, an applied-force vector, and grip force. Trained with weighted cross-entropy (affordance), masked L1 (depth), and MSE losses (forces/width/yaw), it achieves 0.036 m average fingertip error and 81% task success on 10 real-world tasks with unseen objects/environments; ignoring force goals drops success from 90% to 45% under matched starts, highlighting the benefit of force prediction."},{"problem":"Executing long-horizon, contact-rich tasks from an eye-in-hand perspective must be robust to calibration and visual ambiguities; visual-only servoing struggles without explicit force objectives.","method":"A low-level controller performs closed-loop visual-force servoing toward the model’s visual-force goal, minimizing a joint objective over kinematic and force errors (with proportional gains and transformations) to issue incremental Cartesian end-effector and gripper motions, making the system insensitive to global calibration. Action primitives (e.g., approach, grasp, lift, pull, ungrasp) are appended to the text prompt and advanced via a simple state machine, enabling chaining of keyframes and error recovery. In real-robot ablations, removing forces reduces success to 50% over 20 trials and from 90% to 45% in paired trials; ablating depth, pre-training, augmentation, or text conditioning further degrades performance, evidencing the necessity of the joint visual-force objective and the overall system design."}]}
